{"type":"article","slug":"mic/content/27/2/323","journal":"mic","canonical":"https://www.sgmjournals.org/mic/content/27/2/323","meta":{"title":"The Culture of Bordetella pertussis","authors":["Holt, L. B."],"journalTitle":"Journal of General Microbiology","journalAbbrev":"","volume":"27","issue":"2","firstpage":"323","lastpage":"","date":"02/01/1962","doi":"10.1099/00221287-27-2-323","issn":[],"pmid":"13908571","mjid":"mic;27/2/323","section":"","abstractUrl":"http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/27/2/323","fulltextUrl":"","pdfUrl":"http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/reprint/27/2/323.pdf","publicUrl":""},"abstractHtml":"<p>SUMMARY: <i>Bordetella pertussis</i> grew profusely and retained its normal minute coccobacillary form when grown under 0.4 mm. of fluid lying on a Cohen &amp; Wheeler agar medium + charcoal. Microbes grown in this way were fully antigenic in terms of the mouse protection test. It was easy to obtain harvests of 1.2 x 10<sup>11</sup> organisms/ml.</p>","bodyHtml":"","referencesHtml":"","affiliationsHtml":"","correspHtml":"","pdfPath":null,"summaryHtml":"","ccTier":"tier3-abstract","refdomains":0}